## Survival Rates

**Passenger and Crew Survival Statistics:**

| Class       | Number Survived / Total | Survival Rate |
|-------------|------------------------:|--------------:|
| 1st Class   | 201 / 324               |        62.04% |
| 2nd Class   | 118 / 284               |        41.55% |
| 3rd Class   | 181 / 709               |        25.53% |
| Crew        | 212 / 891               |        23.79% |

Data from: [Encyclopedia Titanica](https://www.encyclopedia-titanica.org/)

---

# Social Class and Survival

> "I can never understand why God would have spared a poor Finnish girl when all those rich people drowned."
> - **Anna Sofia Turja**, a 3rd-class passenger

This quote highlights the disparity in survival rates between different social classes:
- **1st Class**: Higher survival rate, more accessible to lifeboats.
- **Crew and 3rd Class**: Lower survival rates, responsibilities, and location on the ship hindered escape.

![Photo of Anna Sofia Turja](imgs/anna-turja_P1.jpg)

Link to Anna's story: [Encyclopedia Titanica](https://www.encyclopedia-titanica.org/titanic-survivor/anna-sofia-turja.html)

---

# Conclusion

- **The Titanic was among the largest and most luxurious ships of its time.**
- **Her tragic sinking remains a poignant reminder of the importance of safety in maritime travel.**
- **Social class played a significant role in survival chances during the disaster.**
